            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this UK salary sacrifice calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool models a simple UK salary sacrifice arrangement where
                you exchange part of your gross salary for an increased employer
                pension contribution. It compares your position before and after
                the change, using 2024/25 income tax and employee National
                Insurance (NI) rates for England, Wales and Northern Ireland.
              </p>

              <h3>Key assumptions</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Tax year: 2024/25, standard personal allowance of £12,570 (no
                  tapering).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Income tax bands: 20% basic rate up to £50,270, 40% higher
                  rate above that (ignoring additional rate for simplicity).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Employee NI: 8% between the primary threshold (£12,570) and
                  upper earnings limit (£50,270), 2% above that.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Employer NI: 13.8% above the secondary threshold (£9,100),
                  used to estimate the employer’s saving.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Pension contributions are within your annual allowance and do
                  not trigger tapered allowance or other complex rules.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Step‑by‑step calculation logic</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>1. Gross salary and pension contributions</strong>
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Gross salary: \( S \)</li>
                  <li>Employee pension (before sacrifice): \( P_e \)</li>
                  <li>Employer pension (before sacrifice): \( P_{er} \)</li>
                  <li>Extra salary sacrificed: \( S_s \)</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>2. Taxable and NI‑able pay</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Before sacrifice, taxable and NI‑able pay is simply your gross
                  salary:
                </p>
                <p>\( \text{Taxable\_before} = S \)</p>
                <p>
                  After sacrifice, your contractual salary is reduced by the
                  sacrificed amount:
                </p>
                <p>\( \text{Taxable\_after} = S - S_s \)</p>
                <p><strong>3. Income tax</strong></p>
                <p>We apply the personal allowance \( A \) and tax bands:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Taxable income: \( T = \max(0, \text{Taxable} - A) \)</li>
                  <li>
                    Basic rate (20%) on income up to £37,700 (i.e. £50,270 −
                    £12,570).
                  </li>
                  <li>Higher rate (40%) on income above that.</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>4. Employee NI</strong></p>
                <p>We apply NI thresholds:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    NI‑able income: \( N = \max(0, \text{Taxable} - 12{,}570) \)
                  </li>
                  <li>8% on income up to £37,700, then 2% above.</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>5. Employer NI saving</strong></p>
                <p>Employer NI is approximated as:</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{EmpNI} = 13.8\% \times \max(0, \text{Taxable} -
                  9{,}100) \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  The saving is the difference before vs after sacrifice. A
                  chosen percentage of this saving is added to your pension.
                </p>
                <p><strong>6. Take‑home pay and pension</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    Take‑home pay = Taxable pay − income tax − employee NI −
                    employee pension (if any).
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Total pension = employee contributions + employer
                    contributions + employer NI top‑up.
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>Interpreting the results</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Change in take‑home pay</strong> shows how much less
                  cash you receive after salary sacrifice.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Change in total pension funding</strong> shows how
                  much extra is going into your pension each year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective cost per £1 of pension</strong> helps you
                  see how tax‑efficient the sacrifice is.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Benefits and risks of salary sacrifice</h3>
              <h4>Potential benefits</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Employee NI savings on the sacrificed amount.</li>
                <li>Employer NI savings that may be added to your pension.</li>
                <li>
                  Higher total pension contributions for the same (or similar)
                  net cost to you.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h4>Potential drawbacks</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Lower contractual salary may affect:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Mortgage or rental affordability checks.</li>
                    <li>
                      Earnings‑related state benefits or statutory payments.
                    </li>
                    <li>Salary‑linked life cover or income protection.</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  You are giving up current income in exchange for long‑term
                  pension savings.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">
                This calculator is for general information only and does not
                constitute financial advice or tax advice. Tax rules can change
                and their impact depends on your personal circumstances.
                Consider speaking to a regulated financial adviser before making
                decisions about salary sacrifice or pension contributions.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>
                Is salary sacrifice the same as normal pension contributions?
              </h3>
              <p>
                No. With normal employee pension contributions, money is
                deducted from your pay after your gross salary is calculated.
                With salary sacrifice, your contractual salary is reduced and
                your employer pays the sacrificed amount into your pension
                instead. This usually saves employee and employer NI.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I stop or change salary sacrifice later?</h3>
              <p>
                Most schemes allow you to change or stop salary sacrifice, but
                usually only at certain times (for example once a year or after
                a “life event”). Check your employer’s policy and scheme rules.
              </p>

              <h3>Does salary sacrifice affect student loan repayments?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Student loan repayments are based on your post‑sacrifice
                salary, so sacrificing salary can reduce your student loan
                repayments. This may or may not be desirable depending on your
                situation.
              </p>

              <h3>Who should consider getting advice?</h3>
              <p>
                You should strongly consider professional advice if you are a
                higher‑rate or additional‑rate taxpayer, close to the pension
                annual allowance, have complex benefits, or are unsure how
                salary sacrifice might affect your mortgage, protections or
                state benefits.
              </p>
